Temu and Shein are not, to be clear, responsible for all of Meta=E2=80=99s =
growth; in a recent analysis MoffettNathanson put the two companies Meta sp=
end at just under $3 billion year-to-date; Meta=E2=80=99s revenue is up aro=
und $11 billion year-over-year in that same time period. Moreover, this spe=
nd is both more palatable and potentially sustainable than TikTok=E2=80=99s=
 spend was: e-commerce apps are not a strategic threat to Meta =E2=80=94 qu=
ite the opposite in fact =E2=80=94 and also lack network effects to make th=
em self-sustaining entities like TikTok has become. Still, subsidies could =
go away, macro events could intervene, etc.; Meta still deserves the credit=
 for figuring out ATT, but Temu and Shein do make the story a bit more comp=
licated.

That quarter did turn out to be the peak of Temu and Shein's share of Meta =
advertising (just under 7% on Facebook, and just under 4% on Instagram); th=
ey are down to around 4% and 2%, respectively. Still, to the extent their b=
usinesses are impacted by these measures (and notably, an important part of=
 their hedging has been building distribution centers in Mexico) there may =
be some impact on Meta's ad prices. I don't think it will be substantial, h=
owever, particularly since Shopify advertisers =E2=80=94 and maybe even Ama=
zon =E2=80=94 are liable to pick up the slack.

AI and Abundance
----------------

It's worth pointing out that the de minimis exception exists for a good rea=
son: there are a lot of items shipped into the U.S. every year, and it's un=
derstandably difficult to examine everything. The relevant U.S. statute ( h=
ttps://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/19/1321 ) is pretty honest about thi=
s:

The Secretary of the Treasury, in order to avoid expense and inconvenience =
to the Government disproportionate to the amount of revenue that would othe=
rwise be collected, is authorized, under such regulations as he shall presc=
ribe, to=E2=80=A6admit articles free of duty and of any tax imposed on or b=
y reason of importation, but the aggregate fair retail value in the country=
 of shipment of articles imported by one person on one day and exempted fro=
m the payment of duty shall not exceed an amount specified by the Secretary=
 by regulation.

It's also worth pointing out that any item that qualified for the de minimi=
s exception also gets to use what is known as "informal entry", which means=
 much more limited paperwork, no need for a customs bond, etc.; informal en=
try applies to shipments worth less than $2,500. The relevant executive ord=
er ( https://www.politico.com/f/?id=3D00000194-c7ad-d7ea-af97-d7fd78170000 =
) does not, as far as I can tell, change these requirements at all.

To that end, it remains to be seen (1) just how much of a difference these =
tariffs make (and, I should note, the Biden administration made moves to be=
gin closing the loophole for many items, including clothing last fall ( htt=
ps://gembah.com/blog/de-minimis-reform-impact-shein-temu/ ) ), and (2) exac=
tly how the U.S. customs authority handles the onslaught of packages. Indee=
d, it's possible that the largest impact is that the time to process these =
deliveries becomes so long that consumers start to lose interest.

I would also note that this seems like a very interesting problem on which =
AI could be brought to bear. There is a story here about how Internet scale=
 simply crushes a loophole created for an analog world; perhaps there is a =
solution in which AI's ability to ingest and understand vast amounts of dat=
a could make sense of the chaos in a way that preserves the convenience whi=
le solving a problem of abundance. Of course the chasm between theory and r=
eality is a massive one, particularly in terms of government bureaucracy, b=
ut I do think this is but one of many examples of where AI will have unexpe=
cted benefits.

